   {:e #blake3 "847012bbbdeae7623c8298cb1a85840268b22411fa3a832f96ee5c1a0da584a2" :a :adr/decision :v "The six :attention/* attributes are reinterpreted as CONNECTION LIFECYCLE attributes applicable to any entity representing a relationship between two other entities. presentation-count becomes activation-count. last-presented becomes last-activated. hebbian-boost is Hebbian co-activation accumulator. learned-weight is Bayesian posterior confidence. calibration-count is Bayesian update count. block-label becomes connection-kind. In Phase D, these attributes are applied to context blocks (existing) and witness pairings (new). In Phase E, they extend to trace links, hypotheses, and cross-project transfer edges." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "847012bbbdeae7623c8298cb1a85840268b22411fa3a832f96ee5c1a0da584a2" :a :adr/problem :v "The attention schema (ATT-0) was designed for context blocks only. But witness pairings, trace links, hypotheses, and attention scores all have the same lifecycle: birth, activation, Hebbian strengthening, Bayesian calibration, decay. Each uses bespoke representations instead of a shared schema." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "847012bbbdeae7623c8298cb1a85840268b22411fa3a832f96ee5c1a0da584a2" :a :comonad/depth :v 1 :op :assert}
